        p(class="w-5/6 pt-2") First established in 1972, the National Marine Sanctuary System has grown to include 13 sanctuaries and one national monument. Managed by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (or “NOAA”), the mission of these marine protected areas cover more than 150,000 square miles of marine and Great Lakes waters from Washington State to the Gulf of Mexico, Lake Huron, and American Samoa. Ranging in size from less than one square mile to 137,792 square miles, each sanctuary site is a special place, managed to conserve, protect, and enhance biodiversity, ecological integrity and cultural legacy.

