        Quiz
        [Correct answer in bold; when correct answer is chosen, a congrats message should pop up (“You are correct!”). Text that should pop up if an incorrect answer is chosen appears in brackets.]

        1. The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary is part of a _____________ system of marine protected areas, managed by the ________________. 
        statewide, Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission
        regional, National Park Service
        national, National Park Service
        regional, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
        national, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration

        [Oops! The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary is one of 13 sanctuaries located across the nation and managed by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, or “NOAA.” NOAA is a federal agency housed under the U.S. Department of Commerce. NOAA programs and services assist citizens across the entire nation.]


        2. The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary was designated in:
            a. 1985
            b. 1990
            c. 2001
            d. 1970
            e. 1995

        [Oops! Congress designated the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary in 1990, amidst concerns over declining water quality, oil exploration, and vessel groundings.]


        3. Which of the following habitats are found in the sanctuary?
            a. Coral reefs
            b. Seagrass meadows
            c. Mangroves
            d. all of the above

        [Oops! The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary includes mangrove, seagrass, and coral reef habitats within coastal and oceanic waters.]


        4. How many species of marine life call the sanctuary home?
            a. 500
            b. 1,000
            c. 3,000
            d. 4,500
            e. More than 6,000

        [Oops! More than 6,000 species of marine life, including more than 500 species of fish and 50 species of coral, call the habitats within the sanctuary home.]


        5. The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary protects North America’s only living coral barrier reef.
            a. True
            b. False

        [Oops! The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary protects North America’s only living coral barrier reef, which is also the third largest barrier reef in the world.]


        6. Which of the following factors did not help prompt the designation of the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary?
            a. Deteriorating water quality
            b. Vessel groundings
            c. Climate change
            d. Threat of oil drilling

        [Oops! The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary was designated by Congress in 1990 amidst concerns over declining water quality, numerous vessel groundings, and the threat of oil drilling.]


        7. How many square nautical miles does the sanctuary protect?
            a. 260
            b. 500
            c. 1,200
            d. 2,900

        [Oops! The sanctuary extends from south of Miami out west past the Dry Tortugas, on both the Gulf and ocean sides, covering 2,900 square nautical miles.]


        8. The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary is one of how many sanctuaries in a national system? 
            a. 5
            b. 8
            c. 13
            d. 25

        [Oops! NOAA’s Office of National Marine Sanctuaries manages 13 sanctuaries in the United States and co-manages one national marine monument in Hawaii.]

        9. Establishment of the Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary incorporated which two preexisting national marine sanctuaries?
            a. Duck Key and Key Largo
            b. Key Largo and Looe Key
            c. Looe Key and Sugarloaf Key
            d. Sugarloaf Key and Key West

        [Oops! Key Largo National Marine Sanctuary was designated in 1975 and Looe Key National Marine Sanctuary was designated in 1981. These two sanctuaries became a part of the larger Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary when it was established in 1990.]


        10. The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary begins one mile offshore and extends from Key Largo to Key West.
            a. True
            b. False

        [Oops! The sanctuary runs from Miami west to the Dry Tortugas and begins at the mean (or average) high water mark. Essentially, as soon as you step foot in the waters surrounding the Keys, you are in the sanctuary.]


